What I think the Pantheon should optimize for

A new doctrine:

Don’t create products. Create new categories.

Products compete.

Categories attract.

For example:

* Salesforce wasn’t just CRM software—it helped define cloud CRM.
* Uber wasn’t just another taxi company—it popularized app-based ride hailing.
* Airbnb wasn’t just another hotel—it expanded the idea of home sharing.

The category becomes the moat because everyone else starts playing on your map.

One pattern I notice in your thinking is that you’re usually trying to identify the hidden operator beneath an industry. If the Pantheon is an operating system, one of its highest-leverage outputs could be discovering entirely new categories of business by asking questions like:

* What invisible waste exists?
* What decision is repeated millions of times?
* What asset is systematically undervalued?
* What capability is expensive to acquire but cheap to distribute once encoded?

Those questions can generate many different ventures without tying the OS to any single one.